response.name: Sampled by The Prodigy
response.description: The Prodigy are an electronic-music group with roots in the rave scene that gained commercial exposure beyond their native U.K. when big.beat blew up internationally in the mid-to-late 1990s (to chagrin, in America under the guise of the nebulous umbrella term "electronica"). Central producer Liam Howlett is known for his mastery of sampling as well as the breadth of samples selected and the creativity with which they are suited to new purposes in tracks by The Prodigy. From classic funk and soul breakbeats to old.school hip.hop vocals, all the way to an interpolation of the guitar riff from Nirvana's "Very Ape", virtually digging through the crates of songs sampled by The Prodigy represents an education in music itself.

group.wikiBody:
Consisting of the complete "Who's Afraid Of (The Art Of Noise)" album, plus selected tracks from the seminal "Into Battle" record and the classic "Moments In Love" 12" single, "Daft" gathers the most important releases of the band's ZTT era on one CD.

Track 1, "Love", is the track called "Moments In Love (Beaten)" on the original singles, it's just mastered with a few extra seconds of silence at the end.
Track 16, "(Three Fingers Of) Love", is the track called "Love Beat" on the original singles, but with the spoken intro edited out.

Many editions are mastered with left-channel noise at 0:55 in "Donna", causing an audible glitch.


Amazon
MusicBrainz

Country: GB
Barcode: 5055041804907
Tracks: 16

Track list:
  1. Love
  2. A Time for Fear (Who’s Afraid)
  3. Beat Box (Diversion One)
  4. The Army Now
  5. Donna
  6. Memento
  7. How to Kill
  8. Realisation
  9. Who’s Afraid (of the Art of Noise)
  10. Moments in Love
  11. Bright Noise
  12. Flesh in Armour
  13. Comes and Goes
  14. Snapshot
  15. Close (to the Edit)

group.wikiBBcode:
Consisting of the complete "Who's Afraid Of (The Art Of Noise)" album, plus selected tracks from the seminal "Into Battle" record and the classic "Moments In Love" 12" single, "Daft" gathers the most important releases of the band's ZTT era on one CD.

Track 1, "Love", is the track called "Moments In Love (Beaten)" on the original singles, it's just mastered with a few extra seconds of silence at the end.
Track 16, "(Three Fingers Of) Love", is the track called "Love Beat" on the original singles, but with the spoken intro edited out.

Many editions are mastered with left-channel noise at 0:55 in "Donna", causing an audible glitch.

torrents.description:
Ripped in EAC secure with log and cue.

The differences between this and the explicit are a doozy.

+ Some songs have different mixing. "Shame on a Nuh," "Can It Be All So Simple," and "C.R.E.A.M." seem to all sound audibly different than their explicit counterparts.

+ "Bring Da Ruckus", "Wu-Tang: 7th Chamber", the untracked "Intermission," and "Wu-Tang: 7th Chamber Part II" are all absent from this version.

+ "Shame on a Nuh" has some new overdubs on it by Ol' Dirty Bastard, even at the beginning claiming that the edit was for the radio. Also, the kung-fu movie sample in the beginning of this track is slightly shorter than on the explicit album. ODB mostly just says "NUH!" in place of the offensive word in the title, along with other lyrics like "I keep 'nuff stains in my drawers", "Don't front the style," "Do you wanna get your teeth knocked on ouuuuuuut?" Then he also yells "WHAT?!" over a bleep on some of Method Man's censor.

+ "Clan in Da Front," "Method Man", "Da Mystery of Chessboxin'," and "Protect Ya Neck" all seem to censor their words with kung-fu sound effects.

+ "Clan in Da Front"'s original opening from the explicit version is absent. The song opens at an uninterruped clip from a kung-fu movie that is slightly talked over on the explicit version, and ends with the opening of the skit at the beginning of "Wu-Tang: 7th Chamber" but quickly fades to another clip from a kung-fu movie that I don't believe is on the explicit album anywhere.

+ "Can It Be All So Simple" has some retakes for lyrics and I believe is the same version used in the music video.

+ "Method Man" for some reason jumped the tracklist to be all the way up here instead of near the end of the album.

+ Just a small thing - the Shaolin Sword/Wu-Tang Sword separation on the tracklist is different. On the explicit version, Wu-Tang Sword starts at "Da Mystery of Chessboxin'." Here, Shaolin Sword ends with it.

+ "Wu-Tang Clan Ain't" is just am edit where practically every censor is reversed.

+ "C.R.E.A.M." is the single/video edit for the song. Some of the lyrics are rerecorded ("So I got with a sick type clique and went all out." "Yo, brotha respect mine.") Not to mention for some reason, a lyric in the explicit version that for some reason got cut out is present here. "Trying to get a hold on what I could not touch." However, the second verse vocals seem to only be in the left channel? Don't know why. There's also some beat changes in this version that aren't in the album cut.

+ "Protect Ya Neck" is missing the radio interlude from the album, which means that no one talks over the opening of the song with "Wu-Tang again?" "Aw, yeah, again and again!"

+ Pretty sure there's no edits made in "Tearz" as there's nothing to cut out, but the opening skit is gone, and the end of it they have the untracked "Conclusion" pasted to the end.

group.wikiBody:
Jailbreak was such a peak that it was inevitable that its follow-up would fall short in some fashion and Johnny the Fox, delivered the same year as its predecessor, did indeed pale in comparison. What's interesting about Johnny the Fox is that it's interesting, hardly a rote repetition of Jailbreak but instead an odd, fitfully successful evolution forward. All the same strengths are still here -- the band still sounds as thunderous as a force of nature, Phil Lynott's writing is still graced with elegant turns of phrase, his singing is still soulful and seductive -- but the group ramped up the inherent drama in Lynott's songs by pushing them toward an odd, half-baked concept album. There may be a story within Johnny the Fox -- characters are introduced and brought back, at the very least -- but it's impossible to tell. If the album only had an undercooked narrative and immediate songs, such digressions would be excusable, but the music is also a bit elliptical in spots, sometimes sounding theatrical, sometimes relying on narration. None of this falls flat, but it's never quite as gripping as Jailbreak -- or the best moments here, for that matter, because when Johnny the Fox is good, it's great, as on the surging "Don't Believe a Word" or the elegiac "Borderline." These are the reasons why Johnny the Fox is worth the extra effort, because it does pay off even if it isn't quite as good as what came immediately before -- or immediately afterward, for that matter.

Track list:
  1. Johnny
  2. Rocky
  3. Borderline
  4. Don't Believe a Word
  5. Fools Gold
  6. Johnny the Fox Meets Jimmy the Weed
  7. Old Flame
  8. Massacre
  9. Sweet Marie
  10. Boogie Woogie Dance

torrents.description:
This Universal UK/Geffen release was cut from a different set of master tapes with a significantly different mix of the album (especially "Heart Shaped Box" and "All Apologies"). This pressing contains matrix codes A33 9124 536 S1 320 and A33 9124 536 S2 320 stamped into the deadwax. It is generally accepted but not confirmed that this is Steve Albini's original, unaltered mix of the album.

http://www.discogs.com/Nirvana-In-Utero/release/841259

rip by pbthal
Turntable: VPI Scoutmaster with Trans-Fi Terminator Air Bearing Linear Tracing Tonearm
Cartridge: Audio-Technica AT33PTG
Phono Preamp: Pro-Ject TubeBox
Soundcard: E-MU 1212
All rips are recorded in full 24bit 192khz resolution and then resampled to 44/24 for manual click repair.
They are then dithered to standard redbook 16bit/44khz
I use IzotopeRX Advanced for all resampling/dithering

torrents.description:
In Utero Universal Music UICY-75875 2013

20th Anniversary Edition. "Super Deluxe Boxset". 

"Limited Edition 3 CDS + 1 DVD, 

56 page special collector's book with unreleased photos and exclusive memorabilia, rare double-sided poster, 

74 unreleased tracks/mixes - 89 total tracks 

- Remastered Original Album + Complete B-Sides 
- Bonus Tracks From The Original Release 
- Original Album Newly Mixed 
- 11 Unreleased Demos 
- MTV's Live & Loud complete concert on DVD & CD with 8 Songs not originally broadcast + rehearsals and tv performances including 3 songs from the final Nirvana concert" 

CD1-15 to 17, 19, 20 + all tracks from CD2, CD3 & DVD are previously unreleased. 

Front cover includes a "pregnant anatomical angel" magnet. 

CDs Aprox Run Time: 223 mins 
DVD Aprox Run Time: 125 mins 
DVD Audio DTS 5.1 Surround Sound, Dolby Digital 5.1 Surround Sound, Dolby Digital Stereo. 
DVD Picture Aspect: 4:3 Full Screen 

* Japanese-only limited edition SHM-CD. 
* Digitally remastered with superior sound quality. 
* Complete obi-strip & Japanese introductory/lyrics sheets included. 
* SHM-CD (Super High Material CD), fully compatible with standard CD players, enables greater transparency, more open sound, lower distortion and better resolution that leads to more sound details. 
* SHM-CD achieves higher quality audio through the use of a polycarbonate plastic with improved transparency derived from LCD display manufacturing technologies.

[b]There are multiple editions labeled SD 8236.  Please research before reporting as a dupe.[/b]

[b]This edition[/b]: https://www.discogs.com/Led-Zeppelin-Led-Zeppelin-II/release/4088425

[quote=discogs]US 1st pressing, featuring Robert Ludwig's "hot" mastering on both sides. These were withdrawn early because the high bass levels caused low-grade cartridges to mistrack, leading people to return the album on the belief that it was defective. Another engineer was then hired to recut a much less "hot" version of the album, and that is the far more common version. 

Labels include "MO" suffix (indicating Monarch pressing) and "Mfg By Atlantic Recording Corp., 1841 Broadway, New York, N.Y.".

Some copies came with one or two hype stickers: one mentioning Whole Lotta Love and the other with a tracklisting.[/quote]

1. The Beginning Of The End - Super Woman 04:57
2. The Beginning Of The End - Trip To Nowhere 05:22
3. The Beginning Of The End - Jamaica 06:09
4. The Beginning Of The End - I've Got The News 05:02
5. The Beginning Of The End - Falling Apart At The Seams 03:50
6. The Beginning Of The End - That's What I Get 06:49
7. The Beginning Of The End - Bluestrain 03:46
8. The Beginning Of The End - Jump In The Water 04:15
9. The Beginning Of The End - Bahamian Boogie 03:15

Strut presents the definitive reissues of two all-time classic Caribbean soul and funk albums, The Beginning Of The End’s ‘Funky Nassau’ (1971) and ‘Beginning Of The End’ (1976).

Emerging from Nassau in the Bahamas in 1971, the band was formed around the Munnings brothers (Ray, Leroy and Frank) and the first song they recorded, ‘Funky Nassau’, became a No. 1 Billboard R’n’B hit, selling over a million copies. “We wanted to create something new,” remembers Ray Munnings, “something that was truly Bahamian. We loved funk but wanted to include elements of junkanoo, the indigenous music of The Bahamas.” An album was written within a week and recorded at Criteria Studios in Miami. “We brought in more Bahamian themes, like ‘Monkey Tamarind’, a wild fruit that grows there.”

By the time of their second album in 1976, the band was managed by Don Taylor, also Bob Marley ’s manager. “Don took us to Byron Lee’s studio in Jamaica and used Teddy Randazzo (Little Anthony & The Imperials) to direct the sessions,” recalls Munnings. “He gave us more of an uptempo jazz funk sound with Chicago-style horns.” The album led to a run of incredible bad luck. Booked to support Marvin Gaye’s ’What’s Goin’ On’ tour, the US Musicians Union stepped in and ordered a US group to fill the slot. They were then added onto a major Bob Marley tour in 1976 before he injured his foot, cancelling all dates.

These definitive official reissues of ‘Funky Nassau’ and ‘Beginning Of The End’ are remastered by The Carvery from original tapes and feature full length tracks from the studio sessions. Both albums feature a history of the albums and the band by vocalist Ray Munnings, alongside rare photos. ‘Beginning
Of The End’ appears on loudpress 2LP for the first time. The CD
edition features both albums + all extra singles recorded by the band.

KEY POINTS:
- Definitive releases of classic Caribbean albums from 1971 and 1976
- Remastered by The Carvery from original tapes
- Albums include full album histories by vocalist Ray Munnings
- Full promo campaign led by Ray Munnings with European gigs
planned from Summer onwards

FOR FANS OF:
Caribbean funk, Gilles Peterson, Curtis Mayfield, James Brown, KC & The Sunshine Band, King Sporty, Bill Withers, Shuggie Otis, Norman Jay ‘Good Times’, The Temptations, Eddy Grant

released December 6, 2017

torrents.description:
[b][size=2]Analog Transfer and rip Info[/size][/b]

This is from an absolutely mint original pressing of the LP, minimal click removal was done as it was so clean. The space between tracks was left at the end of each song, so the playlist reflects the exact timing of the original LP sequence. foobar2000 returns a value of DR=13, very decent.

=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=--=-

VPI HW-16.5 vacuum powered record cleaning machine
Technics SL-1200 Mk III turntable with Denon DL-103 moving coil cartridge, Audio-Tecnica record stabilizer
Acurrus P-10 stand-alone phono preamp in MC position / flat setting.
Metric Halo 2882 audio interface @ 24-bit / 96 kHz
All major clicks removal and balance adjustments performed manually.
Edited in Sound Forge 11 on PC workstation.
Fade-in / Fade-out to digital silence only after program material completely drops below noise floor.

Encoded into 24-bit/96kHz .flac files using FLAC frontend 1.7 - Level 8 - verification - replay gain disabled.
FLAC tags written and checked with Softpointer Tag&Rename 3.6 

Album artwork scanned at 300DPI and posted as .png

torrents.description:
This is a vinyl rip I did of Nirvana's Nevermind album. It's the German re-pressing by Universal with the catalogue number 424 425-1. I've seen it described as the "holy grail" of Nevermind masters on http://www.stevehoffman.tv/forums/. It was mastered by Willem Makkee in 2001 and is allegedly the only version that was transferred flat from the original mastertapes. This version has really good bottom end and dynamics. It doesn't include Endless, Nameless.

The rip is in 16-bit/44.1 kHz .flac. I ripped with 96k, then downsampled in Audacity; however at the time I had no idea what dithering was and as a result, there is a slightly irking hum at ~5k in the verses of "Something in the Way" and on the first few seconds of "Lounge Act". There are some crackles and pops; if anyone feels inclined to improve on this, feel free to do that and trump this torrent. There are about 5 really malevolent pops (3 on "Smells Like Teen Spirit", 2 on "Polly"), but mostly the record plays well.


Equip: Yamaha P-520 turntable, DK-DNN239 stylus, Sony LBT-A190 tower, a stereo cable, Conexant HD Audio sound card, Audacity.

Songs have been wave-gained:
extra gain UNCHECKED
hard limiter UNCHECKED
no clipping prevention CHECKED (only the previously mentioned pops are audibly clipped, and one transient on Somethin

torrents.description:
This is a vinyl rip I did of Nirvana's Nevermind album. It's the German re-pressing by Universal with the catalogue number 424 425-1. I've seen it described as the "holy grail" of Nevermind masters on http://www.stevehoffman.tv/forums/. It was mastered by Willem Makkee in 2001 and is allegedly the only version that was transferred flat from the original mastertapes. This version has really good bottom end and dynamics. It doesn't include Endless, Nameless.

The rip is in 16-bit/44.1 kHz .flac. I ripped with 96k, then downsampled in Audacity; however at the time I had no idea what dithering was and as a result, there is a slightly irking hum at ~5k in the verses of "Something in the Way" and on the first few seconds of "Lounge Act". There are some crackles and pops; if anyone feels inclined to improve on this, feel free to do that and trump this torrent. There are about 5 really malevolent pops (3 on "Smells Like Teen Spirit", 2 on "Polly"), but mostly the record plays well.


Equip: Yamaha P-520 turntable, DK-DNN239 stylus, Sony LBT-A190 tower, a stereo cable, Conexant HD Audio sound card, Audacity.

Songs have been wave-gained:
extra gain UNCHECKED
hard limiter UNCHECKED
no clipping prevention CHECKED (only the previously mentioned pops are audibly clipped, and one transient on Something in the Way inaudibly so)

torrents.description:
Transferred with a Technics SL-QD33 turntable with standard tonearm and an Audio Technica AT3482P stylus. Preamp is a BBE FJB-200X Phono Preamp. Recorded at 24 bit, 96 kHz via a Creative X-Fi USB soundcard in Soundforge 14. Sides normalized then split into individual tracks. Minimal manual declicking performed via iZotope RX 8. Files then converted to FLAC level 8 and tagged in foobar.

This pressing sounds good but has a bit of surface noise, especially at the end of Polly. I didn't do much work on the files as I don't think they really need it, but this definitely isn't on par with a pbthal grade rip or whatnot. Nonetheless, I think it sounds pretty darn good.

Also, the 7" includes Endless, Nameless, Even in His Youth and Aneurysm (the version from the Smells Like Teen Spirit single).
